anty Frandson, Aeents, Skagway\nIT RECIPROCITY SMOKER\nThe so-eaUci Reciprocity smoker\ngiven last night by the winners In the\nlate membership contest of the Arctic\nBrotherhood tcok place last night at A.\nB. halt and was the oocailon of one of\nthe most thoroughly enjoyable enter\ntainments ever held in Skagway.\nThe smoker was inspired by the\nleader of thfe winning team, Mr. Ed.\nCulbertson, and was carried out under\nhis direction in large measure. Many\nfeatures were entirely novel to such\nthings in this city. In the first place\nthe old banquet board was done away\nwith, the hall being tilled instoad with\nlittle square tables just big enough for\nfour, all dressed in cheerful colors and\nlaid with individual service. The tables\nwere olose enough together to main\naln as much sociability with the sur\nrounding tables ad cou'd have\nbsen gettcn oat of the long and\nformal table and a whole\nlot mo. e for all the guests were set at\nease, able to move about, inspired to\nspeak to their neighbors above a whis\nper at once and without waiting for the\nftncorklng influence of the refresh\nmenu.\nOn the d <is of the Arctic Chief sat\nthe toastmoster of the evening, Dr. L.\nS. Keller, and oo his right Arctic Chief\nRobert Sheldon, and on the left District\ndeputy Grand Arctic Chief M. S\nWhlttler. The desk and hall were\ntastefully dressed.\nThe tables were of course filled and\nthe service of the supper proceeded\nwith as smoothly as the fare was de\nlightful.\nDr. Keller, presided with that grace\nthat has distinguished him through a\nlongsorlesof such occasions, Introduc\ning the spaakers with quip and side\nstep that make for a night moat excel\nlently spent, carrying pleasing memo\nries forev r. Tbe addresses .vere all\nshort, sharp to tho point, the music full\nof enoorcs insomuch that the alTair was\ncarried just well over the midnight\nhour without a flaw. Following is the\nprogram which was carried out just as\nit it as writ although it was writ with\nout the knowledge of any party to it\nuntil they arrived in the hall. The\nprograms were, by the way, handsome\nly printed for tho occasion.\nSelection.. A. B. Orchestra\nToast \"The Order\" H. B. LeFevre\nSong Monty Snow\nToast \"The Winners\". .Frank W?bster\nToast 'TheTr-ii\" S. W. Woll\nMandolins and guitar trio\nD'ap 'S, Snow, Ask\nToast \"The Looscrs\". .E. M. Culbertson\nToast \"The Can-pCook\". Wm. Caoavan\nToast \"The Mushes\" Wm. Britt\nQuartette Snow, Ask, Ciemenger,\nHillery\nToast \"Tha New Members\"\nH. a. Drap r\nToast \"The Camp\" M. S. Whittler\nDuet Snow, Ask\nToast \"Sister Societies\" M. Bridge\nToast \"The Ladies\" (Th.^ Real Camp\nCooks) R. Sheldon\nSelection A. B. Orchestra\nThe committee! were ns follow:\nEntertainment? M. Bridge. P. H.\nGanty, G. Wm. Ask. Monty Snow, Dan\nBayless.\nRefreshn ents? Wm. Canavan, Rob\nert Matter, C. C. Shea, Fred Fanio, E.\nM. Culbertson.\nService? P. M. Hern C. C. Rowe, A.\nRapuzzi, A. J. Baker.\nAt Elks hall the ladies night was\ncarried off with equal success. The de\ntails of which will be given in their\nproper place in the society department*\nGeorge D. Travis, Peter Richen, Jack\nReagh, Lyman Annable. A. Rothaker\nand William Ross, who came upon tl a\nBeatrice, put in a part of the time on\nboard evolving a new secret order\nwhich, \"before they reached the dock at\nSkagway was fully launched. It is\nchristened the \"Lailey Miklites,\" or\nBlack Bears. The principles of the\norder are convivial and benevolejt.\nThe name comes from the Chinook.\nThe founders put the principles of the\norder in practice on the way up.\nDo you attend\nDances\nCard Parties or\nOther Social\nFunctions?\nThen you should have an\nEvening Suit and a\nDinner Coat\nNine out of every ten ifr\nol the\nPull Dress\nSuits\nIn this town came from our\nStore\nWe always have a line of sues\non hand or we will take\nyour measure.\nAnd we will Guarantee a fit,\n0<ty$oit (f Co.\n|cft* Owe Price glotbim-foutil) and. Broad way j","height":"22920"